 in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Armenia]]\n[[Category:Death in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Politicides]]\n[[Category:Stalinism]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1937]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1938]]\n[[Category:Soviet phraseology]]\n", "name_user": "138.75.140.173", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMoscow Trials)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Purge"}
{"title_page": "The Scribe (UCCS)", "text_new": "[[File:The Scribe 2016 Logo.png|thumb|Copyright of ''The Scribe''|alt=newspaper, university of colorado]]\n'''''The Scribe''''' is the official school [[newspaper]] for the [[UCCS|University of Colorado Colorado Springs]] campus, published since 1966.<ref>http://scribe.uccs.edu/</ref>\n\nA typical issue has 12 pages, featuring Letters to and from the Editor; Opinion; Science & Business, discussing the science and business stories relevant to the students; Life on the Bluffs, featuring feedback from the students; Culture, with events and reviews; and Sports.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://scribe.uccs.edu/ The Scribe website]\n* [http://www.uccs.edu UCCS homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scribe}}\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in Colorado]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Colorado Springs]]\n\n\n{{Colorado-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:The Scribe 2016 Logo.png|thumb|Copyright of ''The Scribe''|alt=newspaper, university of colorado]]\n'''''The Scribe''''' is the official [[newspaper]] for the [[UCCS|University of Colorado Colorado Springs]] campus, published since 1966.<ref>http://scribe.uccs.edu/</ref>\n\nA typical issue has 12 pages, featuring Letters to and from the Editor; Opinion; Science & Business, discussing the science and business stories relevant to the students; Life on the Bluffs, featuring feedback from the students; Culture, with events and reviews; and Sports.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://scribe.uccs.edu/ The Scribe website]\n* [http://www.uccs.edu UCCS homepage]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scribe}}\n[[Category:Student newspapers published in Colorado]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Colorado Springs]]\n\n\n{{Colorado-newspaper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Davymellado", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Scribe_(UCCS)"}
{"title_page": "Adam Bennett", "text_new": "{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Adam Bennett\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|3|30|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Georgetown, Ontario|Georgetown]], [[Ontario|ON]], [[Canada|CAN]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 206\n| position = [[Defenceman]]\n| shoots = Right \n| team = \n| league = \n| played_for = [[Chicago Blackhawks]]<br>[[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| ntl_team =\n| draft = 6th overall\n| draft_year = 1989\n| draft_team = [[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| career_start = 1990\n| career_end = 1996\n}}\n'''Adam Bennett''' (born March 30, 1971, in [[Georgetown, Ontario|Georgetown]], [[Ontario]]) is a former professional ice hockey [[defenceman]] and coach.  He was selected in the first round of the [[1989 NHL Entry Draft]], 6th overall, by the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBennett played junior with the [[Sudbury Wolves]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]].  In his first season, he was drafted by the Blackhawks, but he played two more years in junior, culminating in an all-star selection at the end of the 1990\u201391 season.  He turned professional immediately after the junior season ended, fitting in three games with the [[Indianapolis Ice]] of the [[International Hockey League (1945\u20132001)|IHL]].\nBennett spent the next two seasons splitting time in the IHL and the NHL, before finally being dealt to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] at the start of the [[1993\u201394 NHL season]].  He played a career high 48 games for the Oilers, in what would be his last NHL season.  He played just two more years of professional hockey, with the [[Cape Breton Oilers]] of the [[American Hockey League|AHL]] and the [[Richmond Renegades]] of the [[East Coast Hockey League|ECHL]].\n\n== Post-playing career ==\nBennett joined the [[Mississauga Ice Dogs]] of the OHL as an assistant coach for the 1998\u201399 season.  Adam is the GM and Head Coach of Clearwater Prep Hockey Academy https://clearwaterprep.com in Clearwater, Florida.\n\n== Awards ==\n*1991 - OHL Second All-Star Team\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[regular season|Regular&nbsp;season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"5\" | [[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n\n|- \n\n|- \n\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1988\u201389 OHL season|1988\u201389]]\n| Sudbury Wolves\n| OHL\n| 66\n| 7\n| 22\n| 29\n| 133\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-  \n| [[1989\u201390 OHL season|1989\u201390]]\n| Sudbury Wolves\n| OHL\n| 65\n| 18\n| 43\n| 61\n| 116\n| 7\n| 1\n| 2\n| 3\n| 23\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1990\u201391 OHL season|1990\u201391]]\n| Sudbury Wolves\n| OHL\n| 54\n| 21\n| 29\n| 50\n| 123\n| 5\n| 1\n| 2\n| 3\n| 11\n|-  \n| [[1991\u201392 IHL season|1990\u201391]]\n| Indianapolis Ice\n| IHL\n| 3\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 12\n| 2\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1991\u201392 IHL season|1991\u201392]]\n| Indianapolis Ice\n| IHL\n| 66\n| 17\n| 22\n| 39\n| 193\n| 21\n| 10\n| 10\n| 20\n| 51\n|-  \n| [[1991\u201392 NHL season|1991\u201392]]\n| Chicago Blackhawks\n| NHL\n| 5\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 12\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1992\u201393 IHL season|1992\u201393]]\n| Indianapolis Ice\n| IHL\n| 39\n| 8\n| 16\n| 24\n| 69\n| 2\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 2\n|-  \n| [[1992\u201393 NHL season|1992\u201393]]\n| Chicago Blackhawks\n| NHL\n| 16\n| 0\n| 2\n| 2\n| 8\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1993\u201394 AHL season|1993\u201394]]\n| Cape-Breton Oilers\n| AHL\n| 7\n| 2\n| 5\n| 7\n| 7\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|- \n| [[1993\u201394 NHL season|1993\u201394]]\n| Edmonton Oilers\n| NHL\n| 48\n| 3\n| 6\n| 9\n| 49\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1994\u201395 AHL season|1994\u201395]]\n| Cape-Breton Oilers\n| AHL\n| 10\n| 0\n| 3\n| 3\n| 6\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- \n| [[1995\u201396 ECHL season|1995\u201399]]\n| [[Richmond Renegades]]\n| ECHL\n| 5\n| 0\n| 1\n| 1\n| 2\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n\n|- \n\n\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=3 | NHL totals\n! 69\n! 3\n! 8\n! 11\n! 69\n! -\n! -\n! -\n! -\n! -\n|}\n\n== Transactions ==\n*October 7, 1993 - Chicago trades Bennett to Edmonton for [[Kevin Todd]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{icehockeystats|legends=10090}}\n*[http://www.3on3hockey.ca/ Bennett's company home page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Jeremy Roenick]] | title = [[List of Chicago Blackhawks draft picks|Chicago Blackhawks first round draft pick]] | years = [[1989 NHL Entry Draft|1989]] | after = [[Karl Dykhuis]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bennett, Adam}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey defencemen]]\n[[Category:Cape Breton Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Blackhawks draft picks]]\n[[Category:Chicago Blackhawks players]]\n[[Category:Edmonton Oilers players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Ice players]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League first round draft picks]]\n[[Category:People from Halton Hills]]\n[[Category:Richmond Renegades players]]\n[[Category:Sudbury Wolves players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Adam Bennett\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|3|30|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Georgetown, Ontario|Georgetown]], [[Ontario|ON]], [[Canada|CAN]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 206\n| position = [[Defenceman]]\n| shoots = Right \n| team = \n| league = \n| played_for = [[Chicago Blackhawks]]<br>[[Edmonton Oilers]]\n| ntl_team =\n| draft = 6th overall\n| draft_year = 1989\n| draft_team = [[Chicago Blackhawks]]\n| career_start = 1990\n| career_end = 1996\n}}\n'''Adam Bennett''' (born March 30, 1971, in [[Georgetown, Ontario|Georgetown]], [[Ontario]]) is a former professional ice hockey [[defenceman]] and coach.  He was selected in the first round of the [[1989 NHL Entry Draft]], 6th overall, by the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBennett played junior with the [[Sudbury Wolves]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]].  In his first season, he was drafted by the Blackhawks, but he played two more years in junior, culminating in an all-star selection at the end of the 1990\u201391 season.  He turned professional immediately after the junior season ended, fitting in three games with the [[Indianapolis Ice]] of the [[International Hockey League (1945\u20132001)|IHL]].\nBennett spent the next two seasons splitting time in the IHL and the NHL, before finally being dealt to the [[Edmonton Oilers]] at the start of the [[1993\u201394 NHL season]].  He played a career high 48 games for the Oilers, in what would be his last NHL season.  He played just two more years of professional hockey, with the [[Cape Breton Oilers]] of the [[American Hockey League|AHL]] and the [[Richmond Renegades]] of the [[East Coast Hockey League|ECHL]].\n\n== Post-playing career ==\nBennett joined the [[Mississauga Ice Dogs]] of the OHL as an assistant coach for the 1998\u201399 season.  He currently runs his own business, called \"3 on 3 Hockey by Adam Bennett\".\n\n== Awards ==\n*1991 - OHL Second All-Star Team\n\n==Career statistics==\n<pre>\n                                            --- Regular season ---  ---- Playoffs ----\nSeason   Team                        Lge    GP    G    A  Pts  PIM  GP   G   A Pts PIM\n---------------------------------------------------------------------